        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "What is Cron?"
        },
        {
          "type": "definition",
          "value": "Cron is a time-based job scheduler in Linux that automatically runs commands or scripts at specific times, dates, or intervals."
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "We use cron to automate repetitive tasks like backups, system maintenance, alerts, and log cleaning. Cron jobs run in the background without user interaction."
        },
        {
          "type": "table",
          "value": [
            ["Common Use Case", "Example"],
            ["Daily backup", "Run a script every midnight"],
            ["Weekly cleanup", "Delete temp files every Sunday"],
            ["Hourly check", "Monitor system memory every hour"],
            ["Scheduled alert", "Send email reminders automatically"]
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "tip",
          "value": "Cron = Automation. Write once → let it run forever."
        }
      ],
      "video": {
        "platform": "youtube",
        "url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v952m13p-b4"
      }
    },
    {
      "slideId": 2,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Cron Syntax (Timing Structure)"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "Cron follows a 5-field timing format to decide when a job runs. Each field controls a time unit."
        },
        {
          "type": "table",
          "value": [
            ["Field", "Meaning", "Example"],
            ["Minute", "0–59", "0 = start of hour"],
            ["Hour", "0–23", "2 = 2 AM"],
            ["Day of Month", "1–31", "15 = 15th day"],
            ["Month", "1–12", "1 = January"],
            ["Day of Week", "0–6", "0/7 = Sunday"]
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "* * * * * command",
          "description": "Runs every minute (wildcards everywhere)."
        },
        {
          "type": "image",
          "url": "https://contabo.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/blog-head_syntax-of-cron.jpg",
          "alt": "Cron timing structure diagram showing the 5 fields"
        },
        {
          "type": "tip",
          "value": "Think of * as 'any value' → run at all times."
        }
      ],
      "video": null
    },
    {
      "slideId": 3,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Common Cron Job Examples"
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "crontab -e",
          "description": "Open cron editor to add or modify cron jobs."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "@reboot /home/user/script.sh",
          "description": "Runs once every time system boots."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "0 0 * * * /home/user/backup.sh",
          "description": "Run backup script every day at midnight."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "0 */1 * * * free -h >> /home/user/memory.log",
          "description": "Log memory usage every hour."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "30 9 * * 1 echo \"Happy Monday!\"",
          "description": "Send reminder every Monday at 9:30 AM."
        },
        {
          "type": "tip",
          "value": "Use full file paths inside cron — it doesn't load user paths like normal terminal."
        }
      ],
      "video": null
    },


    {
      "slideId": 4,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Managing Cron Jobs"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "Cron jobs are handled through crontab (cron table). You can view, edit, and remove entries easily."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "crontab -e",
          "description": "Edit/add cron jobs"
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "crontab -l",
          "description": "List all cron jobs"
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "crontab -r",
          "description": "Remove all cron jobs (use carefully!)"
        },
        {
          "type": "tip",
          "value": "Always test your script manually before putting it into cron."
        }
      ],
      "video": null
    },


    {
